body:
psalm version: 3.8.5
php version: 7.4.7
issue type:  bug

The following code reproduces the issue:

```
<?php declare(strict_types=1);

namespace PsalmIssue;


class TestInstance
{

}

class Expector
{
    /**
     * @param iterable<string, TestInstance> $input
     */
    public function __construct(iterable $input)
    {
    }
}

/**
 * @param iterable<string, TestInstance> $input
 */
function expectoir(iterable $input): void
{

}


function psalmIssue(): void {
    $a = [
        'a' => new TestInstance(),
        'b' => new TestInstance(),
    ];

    $a += \array_map(fn ($x) => new TestInstance(), ['c' => '']);

    $a += [
        'd' => new TestInstance(),
        'e' => new TestInstance(),
    ];

    new Expector($a);
    expectoir($a);

    /**
     * @param iterable<string, TestInstance> $input
     */
    $cb = function (iterable $input): void {};
    $cb($a);

    /**
     * @param iterable<string, TestInstance> $input
     * @return iterable<string, TestInstance>
     */
    $cb2 = fn (iterable $input): iterable => $input;
    $cb2($a);
}


psalmIssue();
```

```
: InvalidArgument - src/psalm-issue.php:43:18 - Argument 1 of PsalmIssue\Expector::__construct expects iterable<string, PsalmIssue\TestInstance>, array{a: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, b: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, c: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, d: PsalmIssue\TestInstance|mixed, e: PsalmIssue\TestInstance|mixed} provided
    new Expector($a);
```

```
ERROR: InvalidArgument - src/psalm-issue.php:44:15 - Argument 1 of PsalmIssue\expectoir expects iterable<string, PsalmIssue\TestInstance>, array{a: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, b: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, c: PsalmIssue\TestInstance, d: PsalmIssue\TestInstance|mixed, e: PsalmIssue\TestInstance|mixed} provided
    expectoir($a);
```

To my surprise the closure and arrow functions do not throw the same error. Maybe psalm does not read those annotations above closures?

Anyway, even though the array `$a` in the example contains only instances of `TestInstance` class, psalm reports detected type `TestInstance|mixed`. If I remove the call to `array_map`, the values under keys `d` and `e` no longer are detected as `|mixed` and no error is triggered, which is the expected behaviour even if the array_map statement is present.
